Hi Iddo, thanks for posting the question. durable_rules uses JSON as the intermediate format for all rules. That is, all rules can be expressed in JSON. I haven't documented the JSON format, but one thing you can do is un-comment line 1861 in durable.js file (in your node_modules directory). Write your rules using the node.js format, the JSON equivalent will be dumped to the console. 

The case of timers:
```javascript
ruleset('timer', function() {
    whenAny: {
        whenAll: s.count == 0
        // will trigger when MyTimer expires
        whenAll: {
            s.count < 5 
            timeout('MyTimer')
        }
    }
    run: {
        s.count += 1;
        // MyTimer will expire in 5 seconds
        startTimer('MyTimer', 5);
        console.log('Pusle ->' + new Date());
    }

    whenAll: {
        m.cancel == true
    }
    run: {
        cancelTimer('MyTimer');
        console.log('canceled timer');
    }

    whenStart: {
        patchState('timer', { count: 0 }); 
    }
});
```  

The JSON format:  
```javascript
{
  "r_0": {
    "any": [
      {
        "m_0$all": [
          {
            "m_0.m": {
              "$and": [
                {
                  "count": 0
                },
                {
                  "$s": 1
                }
              ]
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "m_1$all": [
          {
            "m_1.m_0": {
              "$and": [
                {
                  "$lt": {
                    "count": 5
                  }
                },
                {
                  "$s": 1
                }
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "m_1.m_1": {
              "$t": "MyTimer"
            }
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  "r_1": {
    "all": [
      {
        "m": {
          "cancel": true
        }
      }
    ]
  }
}
```

The $not operator (none in node.js), means absence of data. In the case above I think you were expecting the semantics to be 'did not match', but that is not exactly how it works. This example is a better illustration on how the operator works (the rule will trigger only if there is no 'balance' event):

```javascript
d.ruleset('risk2', function() {
    whenAll: {
        first = m.t == 'deposit'
        none(m.t == 'balance')
        third = m.t == 'withrawal'
        fourth = m.t == 'chargeback'
    }
    run: console.log('fraud detected ' + first.t + ' ' + third.t + ' ' + fourth.t);

    whenStart: {
        post('risk2', {t: 'deposit'});
        post('risk2', {t: 'withrawal'});
        post('risk2', {t: 'chargeback'});
    }
});
```

The 'does not match' operator for pattern matching has not been implemented yet.

