https://github.com/marshmallow-code/marshmallow/issues/347 is one issue.

Having an envelope parameter on the field is more intuitive, and it saves one from being forced to write a matching `post_dump` method to properly envelope all the relevant fields (how do we know which fields belong where ?) because `envelope` works both ways.

This is how we implement this for a resource object using `post_dump` and `pre_load`:
```python
@pre_load
def __pre_load(self, data):
    result_data = {}
    attributes = data.get('attributes')
    relationships = data.get('relationships')
    if 'id' in data:
        result_data['id'] = data['id']
    result_data['type'] = data.get('type')

    if attributes:
        for attribute, value in attributes.items():
            result_data[attribute] = value
    if relationships:
        for relationship, value in relationships.items():
            result_data[relationship] = value
    return result_data

@post_dump
def __post_dump(self, data):
    result_data = {'attributes': {}, 'relationships': {}, 'links': links}
    for key, value in data.items():
        field = self.fields.get(key)
        if field:
            # 'id' and 'type' members belong at the top of a JSONAPI
            #  document.
            if key == 'id' or key == 'type':
                result_data[key] = value
                continue
            if isinstance(field, RelationshipObject):
                result_data['relationships'][key] = value
            else:
                result_data['attributes'][key] = value
    return result_data
```

Using `envelope`, you just specify where to envelope in each field, and nothing else:
```python
class PoolMemberToJSONAPIResourceObject(ResourceObject):
    """
    PoolMember schema
    """
    __model__ = models.PoolMember

    name = fields.String(envelope=('attributes',), dump_only=True)
    enabled = fields.Boolean(envelope=('attributes',))
    ratio = fields.Integer(envelope=('attributes',))

    node = RelationshipObject(
        'NodeToJSONAPIResourceObject', envelope=('relationships',), required=True)
    pool = RelationshipObject(
        'PoolToJSONAPIResourceObject', envelope=('relationships',), required=True)
    properties = RelationshipObject(
        'PoolMemberPropertyToJSONAPIResourceObject', envelope=('relationships',), many=True)
```

@HelloWorldYyx @alessign Please take a look at the related issue #575.

When you train a classifier with two classes, the classifier has to place its probability so that it sums to 100%. If you show it a tree, even if you would like it to say 0% cat and 0% dog, this is simply not possible the way the problem is formulated. A result of 50% cat and 50% dog would be better, but this is not how the models typically behave unfortunately.

As I wrote in the other issue, it is possible to train such a classifier by introducing a third "other" class. This should make it much more robust to samples outside your named classes, and allow for predictions such as "0% cat, 0% dog, (100% other)".

